    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Species of medium sized oak tree native to the southeast of the United States, from coastal Virginia to central Florida to Texas, growing 20-25 m (65-80 feet) in height, and having a large, circular crown.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Middelgrote eik die inheems is in het zuidoosten van de Verenigde Staten, in het gebied dat zich uitstrekt van de kust van Virginia tot Midden-Florida en Texas. De boom kan 20 tot 25 meter hoog worden en heeft een grote ronde kroon.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一種原生美國東南部的中型櫟樹，分布地區從維吉尼亞州沿海區域、佛羅里達州中部至德州，高度可達20至25公尺（65至80英尺），樹冠大而圓。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
